===Etymology===
French ''Ancient Régime'', ''Old Rule'', ''Old Order''; the word first appeared in English in print in 1794.

===Noun===
'''Ancien Régime''' (''plural:'' (only used for the second definition) '''[[anciens régimes]]''')

# ''Capitalised:'' The aristocratic social and political system established in France under the [[Valois]] and [[Bourbon]] dynasties, overthrown by the French Revolution of 1789.
# ''In lower case:'' A system of government long since supplanted by another; particularly one which possesses the following characteristics:
::* A state of [[feudalism]] under an
::* Absolute monarchy supported by
::* The doctrine of the Divine Right of Kings or 天命 (Tiānmìng - ''Mandate of Heaven''), with the explicit consent of
::* An established church
Essentially, the way in which Europe was organised from circa 8th century to the Modern Age.

===Usage Note===
* Both senses of the term carry pejorative connotations.